  "prompt": "How do you calculate credit hours earned?",
  "response": "Credit hours are a measure of the amount of coursework a student has completed, and they typically reflect the number of hours spent in class per week over a semester. Here\u2019s how you can calculate credit hours earned:\n\n1. **Determine Class Length**: \n   - Standard classes typically meet for a certain number of hours per week. For example, a 3-credit class usually meets for about 3 hours a week for a semester (15 weeks is common for many institutions).\n\n2. **Consider Course Type**: \n   - Different courses may have different credit hour allocations based on the intensity and requirements of the course. For example, lab courses or studio classes may offer more credit hours for the same number of class hours.\n\n3. **Calculate Based on Meeting Hours**:\n   - If a course meets for 1 hour a week and lasts for 15 weeks, that course usually earns 1 credit hour.\n   - For a course that meets for 3 hours a week for the same duration, it typically earns 3 credit hours.\n\n4. **Check for Additional Requirements**:\n   - Some programs require additional work outside of class, such as labs or fieldwork, which can also contribute to credit hours. This is especially true for graduate programs or specialized courses.\n\n5. **Refer to the Institution\u2019s Guidelines**:\n   - Each educational institution has its own policy regarding credit hours, including any variations in how they calculate them. Always refer to the academic catalog or speak with an academic advisor for specific information.\n\nFor example, if you complete a semester with:\n- 1 three-credit course\n- 1 four-credit course\n- 1 two-credit course\n\nYou would calculate your total credit hours earned as:\n\n3 (from the three-credit course) + 4 (from the four-credit course) + 2 (from the two-credit course) = **9 credit hours earned.**\n\nIn summary, to determine credit hours earned, consider the number of classes, the credits each class is worth, and any additional activities required by the course.",
